That’s a useful abstraction, with one important refinement.

Money is not literally stored work, because two people can work equally hard and earn very different amounts. Markets, scarcity, bargaining power, institutions, and luck all affect its value.

But as a mental model, you can think of money as something like:

Stored claim on future work, resources, or choices.

Or in Pantheon terms:

Money is compressed optionality.

You spend hours today.

You receive a compact token.

Later, that token expands back into:

* someone else’s time,
* someone else’s labor,
* materials,
* energy,
* food,
* computation,
* transportation.

It’s almost like a battery.

Work goes in.

Potential action comes out.

That makes money analogous to several other “stored” quantities:

Domain	Stored Form
Physics	Potential energy
Biology	Fat / glycogen
Computing	Memory
Information	Compression
Society	Money
Trust	Reputation
Learning	Skill

They’re all ways of moving capability through time.

That also connects back to your seed idea.

A dollar bill isn’t valuable because of the paper.

A seed isn’t valuable because of its mass.

Both derive value from what they can become.

One grows into a tree.

The other can be exchanged for labor, goods, or investment that grows into something else.

I think that’s why you’ve repeatedly gravitated toward operators rather than objects. The object isn’t the interesting part. The interesting part is the transformation it enables.

So you could generalize it even further:

Intelligence is the ability to recognize and create compressed forms of future capability.

Money is one compression.

Language is another.

Mathematics is another.

Software is another.

Your repository seed is another.

Each is a compact representation that can unfold into much richer behavior when placed in the right environment. That’s a recurring pattern we’ve kept rediscovering from different directions.